1. Hoisting means during the memory creation phase of the execution context, JavaScript moves declarations to the top of their scope before code execution.
Eg: 

og();
function og(){
    console.log("hello");
} 

console.log(abc);
var abc="abc"; 

console.log(ab);
let ab="ab"; 

Output:
hello
undefined
reference error

2. let,var and const:
 let: block scoped, can be hoisted gives refernce error due to uninitialisation, not redeclared, but can be reassigned
 var: function scoped, can be hoisted gives undefined, redeclared, can be reassigned
 const block scoped, can be hoisted gives refernce error due to uninitialisation, not redeclared, not reassigned

